5. Troubleshoot: A client PC is not receiving an IP address from your DHCP server. List 3 possible causes and describe how you would test and fix each one using Windows Server tools.
=>Client Network Configuration Issue
Cause: Client set to static IP instead of DHCP.
Test: On client run ipconfig /all — look for "DHCP Enabled: No".
Fix: Set IPv4 to "Obtain an IP address automatically". Run ipconfig /release then /renew.

DHCP Server Scope or Service Problem
Cause: Scope not activated, exhausted IPs, or DHCP service stopped.
Test: In DHCP Manager, check if scope is green/active and has available addresses. Check Event Viewer (Applications and Services Logs → Microsoft → DHCP-Server).
Fix: Activate scope, restart DHCP Server service (services.msc), or expand scope range.

Network Connectivity / Relay / Firewall
Cause: Client on different subnet without DHCP relay, or firewall blocking UDP 67/68.
Test: Ping server from client. On server: netstat -ano | find "67" to check listening. Check firewall rules (File and Printer Sharing).
Fix: Enable DHCP relay (if routed), open ports, or place client on same subnet/VLAN.
